context: Throughout Europe at this time there was a rapid growth in <a0_0><b5_0>trade<b5_0/><a0_0/> and an associated growth in towns. <a1_0><b6_0>Germany<b6_0/><a1_0/> and the Lowlands had large flourishing towns that grew in comparative peace, in trade and competition with each other, or united for mutual weal, as in the Hanseatic League. <a2_0><b7_0>Civic building<b7_0/><a2_0/> was of great importance to these towns as a sign of wealth and pride. <a3_0><b8_0>England<b8_0/><a3_0/> and <a4_0>France<a4_0/> remained largely feudal and produced grand domestic architecture for their kings, dukes and bishops, rather than grand town halls for their burghers.
